#Tips for effective visulization 1. keep it simple 2. use color to draw attention 3. tell a story

#Principles for effective visulization 1. order matters 2. put long categories on the y-axis 3. keep scales consistent 4. select meaningful colors 5. use meaningful and nonredundant labels

bx <- read_csv("brexit.csv")
## Rows: 1639 Columns: 2
##  Column specification 
## Delimiter: ","
## chr (2): opinion, region
## 
##  Use `spec()` to retrieve the full column specification for this data.
##  Specify the column types or set `show_col_types = FALSE` to quiet this message.
  1. order matters
ggplot(bx, aes(x = opinion)) +
  geom_bar()

fct_infreq():reorder factors levels by frequency

ggplot(bx, aes(x=fct_infreq(opinion))) +
  geom_bar() +
  labs(
    x="opinion",
    y="count"
  ) #clean up labels

alphabetical order is rarely ideal

ggplot(bx, aes(x=region)) +
  geom_bar()

fct_relevel:reorder factor levels using a custom order

bx <- bx %>% 
  mutate(
    region = fct_relevel(
      region,
      "london", "rest_of_south", "midlands_wales", "north", "scot"
    )
  )
ggplot(bx, aes(x=region)) +
  geom_bar()

fct_recode:change factor level names by hand

bx <- bx %>% 
  mutate(
    region = fct_recode(
      region,
      'London' = "london",
      'Rest of South' = "rest_of_south",
      'Midlands / Wales' = "midlands_wales",
      'North' = "north",
      'Scotland' = "scot"
    )
  )
ggplot(bx, aes(x=region)) +
  geom_bar()

2. put long categories on the y-axis

ggplot(bx, aes(x=region)) +
  geom_bar() +
  coord_flip()

ggplot(bx, aes(y=region)) +
  geom_bar()

fct_rev:reverse order of factor levels

ggplot(bx, aes(y=fct_rev(region))) +
  geom_bar() +
  labs(x = "Count",
       y = "Region")

ggplot(bx, aes(y=region, fill=opinion)) +
  geom_bar()

ggplot(bx, aes(y=opinion, fill=region)) +
  geom_bar() +
  facet_wrap(~region, nrow = 1)

ggplot(bx, aes(y=opinion, fill=opinion)) +
  geom_bar() +
  facet_wrap(~region, nrow = 1) +
  guides(fill=FALSE) +
  labs(
    title = "Was Britain right/wrong to vote exit EU?",
    subtitle = "YouGov Survey Results, 2-3 September 2019",
    caption = "Source:https://d25d2506sfb94s.cloudfront.net/cumulus_uploads/document/x0msmggx08/YouGov%20-%20Brexit%20and%202019%20election.pdf",
    x = NULL,
    y = NULL
  )
## Warning: The `<scale>` argument of `guides()` cannot be `FALSE`. Use "none" instead as
## of ggplot2 3.3.4.

ggplot(bx, aes(y=opinion, fill=opinion)) +
  geom_bar() +
  facet_wrap(~region, nrow = 1) +
  facet_wrap(~region,
             nrow = 1,
             labeller = label_wrap_gen(width = 12)) +
  guides(fill=FALSE) +
  labs(
    title = "Was Britain right/wrong to vote exit EU?",
    subtitle = "YouGov Survey Results, 2-3 September 2019",
    caption = "Source: bit.ly/2lCJZVg",
    x = NULL,
    y = NULL
  )

4. select meaningful colors

ggplot(bx, aes(y=region, fill=opinion)) +
  geom_bar(position="fill")

Choose color manually

ggplot(bx, aes(y=opinion, fill=opinion)) +
  geom_bar() +
  facet_wrap(~region, nrow = 1) +
  facet_wrap(~region,
             nrow = 1,
             labeller = label_wrap_gen(width = 12)) +
  guides(fill=FALSE) +
  labs(
    title = "Was Britain right/wrong to vote exit EU?",
    subtitle = "YouGov Survey Results, 2-3 September 2019",
    caption = "Source: bit.ly/2lCJZVg",
    x = NULL,
    y = NULL
  ) +
  scale_fill_manual(values = c(
    "Wrong" = "red",
    "Right" = "green",
    "Don't know" = "grey"
  ))

colorbrewer2

             nrow = 1,

  theme_minimal()

Viridis scale works well with ordinal data

ggplot(bx, aes(y=region, fill=opinion)) +
  geom_bar(position = "fill") +
  scale_fill_viridis_d()

barplot <- ggplot(diamonds, aes(x="", fill=clarity)) +
  geom_bar(width = 1, position = "stack")
barplot

barplot + coord_polar()

barplot + coord_polar(theta = "y")

barplot <- ggplot(diamonds, aes(x="", fill=clarity)) +
  geom_bar(width = 1, position = "dodge")
barplot

Components of a plot 1. a default data set and set of mappings from variables to aesthetics 2. one or more layers -one geommetric object (geom_) -one statistical transformation (stat_) -one position adjustment(position_) 3. one dataset and set of aesthetic mappings 4. a coordinate system(coord_) 5. a facet sepecification(facet_)

md <- read_csv("minard.csv")
## Rows: 48 Columns: 5
##  Column specification 
## Delimiter: ","
## chr (1): direction
## dbl (4): long, lat, surviv, division
## 
##  Use `spec()` to retrieve the full column specification for this data.
##  Specify the column types or set `show_col_types = FALSE` to quiet this message.
md_city <- read_csv("minard-cities.csv")
## Rows: 20 Columns: 3
##  Column specification 
## Delimiter: ","
## chr (1): city
## dbl (2): long, lat
## 
##  Use `spec()` to retrieve the full column specification for this data.
##  Specify the column types or set `show_col_types = FALSE` to quiet this message.
md_temp <- read_csv("minard-temps.csv")
## Rows: 9 Columns: 5
##  Column specification 
## Delimiter: ","
## chr (1): date
## dbl (4): lat, long, temp, days
## 
##  Use `spec()` to retrieve the full column specification for this data.
##  Specify the column types or set `show_col_types = FALSE` to quiet this message.
plot_troops <- ggplot(md) +
  geom_path(aes(x=long,
                y=lat,
                color=direction,
                linewidth=surviv,
                group=division))
plot_troops

plot_both <- plot_troops +
  geom_text(data=md_city, 
            aes(x=long,
                y=lat,
                label=city),
            size=3)
plot_both

library(ggrepel)
plot_all <- plot_both +
  geom_text_repel(data = md_temp, 
            aes(x=long,
                y=lat,
                label=temp),
            size=3.5,
            color="#67a9cf"
            )
plot_all
## Warning: Removed 1 rows containing missing values (`geom_text_repel()`).

ggplot(md) +
  geom_path(aes(x = long,
                y = lat,
                color = direction,
                size = surviv^2,
                group = division),
            lineend = "round") +
  geom_text(aes(x = long,
                y = lat,
                label = city),
            data = md_city,
            size = 3) +
  geom_text_repel(aes(x = long,
                      y = lat,
                      label = temp),
                  data = md_temp,
                  size = 3,
                  color="#67a9cf"
                  ) +
  scale_size(range = c(.18,15),
             breaks = (1:3*10^5)^2,
             labels = 
               scales :: comma(1:3*10^5),
             "Survivors") +
  scale_color_manual(values = c("grey50",
                                  "red"), 
                       breaks = c("A",
                                  "R"), 
                       labels = c("Advance",
                                  "Retreat"),
                       "") +
    xlab(NULL) + ylab(NULL) +
    theme(axis.text = element_blank(), 
          axis.ticks = element_blank(), 
          panel.grid = element_blank())
